<H3> <TI>   Japan Environmental News Update (1-15 September 1993) </TI></H3>
<H4>   Mitsubishi Heavy Industries To Market Turbo Refrigeration 
Machine With CFC Substitute </H4>
<F P=102> 946C3801B Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 Sep 93 p 
13--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 946C3801B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Complete text of article obtained through NIKKEI BIZ </F>
DATABASE] 
  [Text] Mitsubishi Heavy Industries has added a new type to 
its line of turbo refrigerating machines for large capacity air 
conditioners by employing "HFC-134a," a CFC substitute, as the 
refrigerant. By adjusting the heat exchange cycle, the new 
machines can be used for heating up to 50&deg;C and for cooling 
to -10&deg;C. 
  HFC-134a has less impact on the environment than "CFC-11" 
and 
does not deplete the ozone layer. The turbo refrigerating 
machines using HFC-134a are the third type to employ a CFC 
substitute, following those with "HCFC-123" and "HCFC-22." 
  The new type consists of six models with different 
refrigeration capabilities ranging from 150 to 400 refrigerating 
tons and priced from &yen;39.5 million to &yen;56 million. Large 
capacity models of up to 7,000 refrigerating tons will be 
developed based on the sales conditions of the smaller models. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

