<H3> <TI>   Japan Environmental News Update (1-15 September 1993) </TI></H3>
<H4>   Nagano City Introduces Electric Vehicle--First Case in 
Prefecture </H4>
<F P=102> 946C3801D Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Sep 93 p 
3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 946C3801D </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Complete text of article obtained through NIKKEI BIZ </F>
DATABASE] 
  [Text] On 1 September, Nagano City introduced an electric 
vehicle and held a ceremony at city hall for its initial 
operation. The vehicle is a lightweight van manufactured by 
Daihatsu and is equipped with lead accumulators. This is the 
first electric vehicle to be introduced in the prefecture. The 
city plans to use it for monitoring pollution in the city and to 
promote recycling. 
  The vehicle is called "E-Car," named after the initial 
English letter for electricity, ecology and environment. The 
white body has an oval design of moss green, pink and light blue 
stripes. 
  Charging facilities have been established in the waste 
processing plant and city hall. The van is capable of driving 
about 130 kilometers for each 8- hour charge. It costs 
&yen;3.162 million, and was partially financed by the 
Environment Agency. 
  Mayor Tsukada looked satisfied, saying, "It has been 
introduced to promote an environment-friendly community. The van 
is quiet and stable." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

