<H3> <TI>   Japan Environmental News Update (1-15 September 1993) </TI></H3>
<H4>   Environment Agency To Increase Acid Rain Monitoring Centers </H4>
<F P=102> 946C3801G Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Sep 93 p 
5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 946C3801G </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Complete text of article obtained through NIKKEI BIZ </F>
DATABASE] 
  [Text] Beginning in FY94, the Environment Agency will add 
seven acid rain monitoring stations over a two-year period to 
reinforce its network. Even though it is believed that serious 
effects of acid rain have not occurred in Japan, the acid rain 
recorded in Japan has been detected to have acidity equivalent 
to that in Europe, where serious effects of acid rain have been 
reported. The agency expects to monitor the conditions in detail 
by strengthening its monitoring system. 
  Although the locations of the new stations have not been 
finalized, they are expected to be established to improve the 
monitoring network in some urban areas, some mountainous areas, 
and areas on the coastline of the Sea of Japan and the East 
China Sea to monitor the effects from China. At the moment, 
there are 30 monitoring stations in major cities, on distant 
islands, etc., with 10 additional stations to be established 
during the current fiscal year. The increase of 7 more stations 
beginning in FY94 will make a total of 47 monitoring stations 
across Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

