<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Moscow Decide on Issues for Nuclear Waste Meetings </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1411183393 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 13 Nov 
93 Evening Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> OW1411183393 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Nobuyuki Tanaka] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 12 Nov -- On 12 November, the first general 
meeting between Japan and Russia was held in Moscow to discuss 
promoting bilateral cooperation in the disposal of nuclear 
waste. Edamura, Japanese ambassador to Russia, and Yegorov, 
Russian vice atomic energy minister, attended the meeting. 
  During the meeting, the two countries agreed that meetings 
of 
experts should be held to discuss the following issues: 1) the 
possible construction of storage facilities for fissionable 
materials from dismantled warheads; 2) the disposal of liquid 
missile fuel; and 3) the dumping of radioactive waste into sea. 
  The Japanese Government has already decided to appropriate 
$100 million to help Russia, Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and Byelarus 
dismantle nuclear materials. The meeting was held to discuss 
details of Japan's aid. 

</TEXT>

