<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Candidate Countries To Maintain Environmental Standards </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1201102194 Brussels EUROPE in English 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BR1201102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Environment--Candidate Countries </F>
Should Be Allowed To Maintain Their Advanced Environmental 
Standards"; as released by Brussels Textline database] 
  [Text] By adopting the Brigit Bjornvig Report (Dk, Rbw) 
[expansion unknown] Parliament's Environment Commission 
supported the "legitimacy" of the requests by Sweden, Austria, 
Finland and Norway to be authorized to maintain their advanced 
standards in environmental protection following their accession 
to the European Union. The Committee stressed that these 
countries: 
  a) would soon be bringing a significant contribution in 
strengthening the EU's environmental legislation; 
  b) must, as far as possible, be authorized by the Council 
and 
Commission to maintain their current environmental standards in 
those fields where the "acquis communautaire" is less advanced. 
She also hoped that these two institutions would begin revising 
this acquis as soon as possible with a view to the harmonization 
of the environmental regulations of an enlarged Europe at the 
highest level. 

</TEXT>

