<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> PAKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Comments on Foreign Secretary's Japan Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0912000093 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in Urdu 1500 
GMT 8 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> BK0912000093 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pakistan is holding consultations with Japan, the 
United States, and other friendly countries to devise an 
acceptable mechanism to achieve the goal of nonproliferation in 
South Asia. 
  A Foreign Office spokesman, answering a question about the 
foreign secretary's visit to Japan and his talks in Tokyo with 
Japanese officials, said that Japan has shown interest in 
participating in a regional conference on nuclear 
nonproliferation. The conference was proposed by Pakistan. He 
said the foreign secretary attended the sixth session of the 
Pakistan-Japan Joint Commission and held talks on bilateral and 
economic relations. The Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty [NPT] 
and arms control issues were also discussed. The spokesman said 
Pakistan reaffirmed its stance that it is ready to ratify the 
NPT, provided that India is willing to do so simultaneously. 

</TEXT>

