<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Tightens Control Over Arms Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3011170193 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1511 GMT 30 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3011170193 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow November 30 TASS -- The Persian Gulf 
countries believe that "Russia as a great power must act as a 
guarantor of stability in the world and in the region," Russian 
Vice Premier Aleksandr Shokhin told a press conference devoted 
to the results of his last week's trip to the United Arab 
Emirates and Russian arms export. 
  A press release circulated at the press conference said 
Russia earned 2.3 billion dollars from arms sales in 1992, and 
has set sights on earning about nine billion dollars annually. 
It is hardly sensible to turn away from this source of income 
which helps solve numerous problems facing this country, the 
press release says. 
  It also stressed that Russian arms exports are not 
politically motivated. They are purely commercial in nature and 
are not directed against the interests of any separate country. 
"Moreover, we are prepared to discuss with the world exporters 
a reduction of arms exports on a reciprocal basis," the paper 
said. 
  Russia is now orientating its arms sales towards financially 
and politically stable Middle East, Latin American, and 
Southeast Asian countries. Good prospects exist for cooperation 
with China in the military field, the release said. 
  Responding to questions from journalists, Aleksandr Shokhin 
expressed confidence that the privatisation process underway in 
Russia, including the sell-off of military enterprises, will not 
impair state control over Russia's arms export. He recalled 
that Russia had set up a special system of control over its arms 
sales, and control is now being further tightened. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

