<DOCNO> FBIS3-60589 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptnd001___94051" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TND-93-001 </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:PROLIFERATION ISSUES 

<DATE1>  6 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Addresses CSCE Meeting on `New Challenges' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3011124793 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1049 
GMT 30 Nov 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3011124793 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Sergey Startsev and </F>
Georgiy Shmelev] 
  [Text] Rome, 30 Nov -- New challenges to security and 
cooperation in Europe are taking on an increasingly dramatic 
character. The threat of aggressive nationalism has replaced 
that of totalitarianism. This was stated today by Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev, speaking at the fourth session 
of the Council of Foreign Ministers of the CSCE which is taking 
place in Rome. 
  The fact that manifestations of aggressive nationalism are 
gripping not only eastern but also central and western Europe 
demands much more decisive and urgent reactions, the minister 
emphasized. He considers that what is needed above all is 
"unambiguous moral condemnation of these manifestations." The 
Russian side has therefore proposed the adoption of a document 
in which the CSCE participant states would declare that 
intolerance and xenophobia are incompatible with a civilized 
Europe standing on the threshold of the 21st century. 
  In A. Kozyrev's opinion it is important that the Rome forum 
should adopt measures to support and strengthen the institution 
of the CSCE's Supreme Commissar for National Minority Affairs. 
"There should be a guaranteeing of the effectiveness of 
humanitarian law in armed conflicts engendered by aggressive 
nationalism," he declared. 
  Andrey Kozyrev believes the CSCE has another important task; 
namely, to reinforce its peacekeeping potential in order to 
settle conflicts where agressive nationalism has led to 
bloodshed. He pointed to the special role of CSCE observers, 
who are "working heroically in South Ossetia, the Dniester 
region, and Abkhazia, acting hand in hand with the Russian 
Federation peacekeeping forces." 
  In this connection A. Kozyrev called upon the CSCE to 
support 
Russia's peacekeeping efforts and to reexamine the issue of CSCE 
observers returning to "hot spots" in the territory of former 
Yugoslavia. The minister thinks it would be correct for the 
CSCE to make the authorities in Belgrade aware that constructive 
steps on their part would open up prospects for the FRY to 
rejoin the CSCE. The minister believes that the CSCE should take 
upon itself the political coordination of peacekeeping efforts, 
within the framework of such organizations as NACC [North 
Atlantic Cooperation Council], CIS, NATO, and the Western 
European Union. 
  A. Kozyrev described as a fresh and unprecedented challenge 
to European security the fact that "for the first time since the 
signing of the Treaty on Nonproliferation of Nuclear Weapons in 
1968, we are seeing under way in Europe not a strengthening of 
the nonproliferation regime and new states joining it, but 
essentially the reverse." "One of the CSCE member states," the 
minister pointed out, "has, contrary to the obligations it 
assumed, officially announced that it possesses nuclear weapons. 
Furthermore, we are speaking here of an awesome nuclear 
potential exceeding that of some powers possessing nuclear 
weapons." The Russian Federation minister believes that this 
creates a completely new situation in terms of security on the 
continent of Europe. A. Kozyrev called upon the CSCE to make a 
determined declaration of the inviolability of the 
Nonproliferation Treaty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

