<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Fuel Rods Stolen From Murmansk Naval Base </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0312142993 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1500 GMT 2 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> PM0312142993 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast: Video report from Murmansk by </F>
Valeriy Anuchin and Oleg Kul, identified by caption; figures in 
brackets denote broadcast time in GMT in hours, minutes, and 
seconds] 
  [Text] [150929] [video opens with shot of reporter against 
snow-covered landscape with buildings] 
  [Anuchin] Over there behind me are Northern Fleet storage 
dumps. The security regulations there prevent us from showing 
them to you, but I can tell you that there has been an emergency 
there. Paramilitary protection service personnel here have 
discovered a theft of nuclear fuel as used by nuclear 
submarines. Three uranium control rods have been stolen. A 
crime file has been opened. The theft is being investigated by 
a special interdepartmental group which includes representatives 
of the Fleet Military Prosecutor's Office, military 
counterintelligence organs, and the Internal Affairs 
Directorate. The theft, the specialists believe, was committed 
by people familiar with this kind of nuclear fuel. That is, the 
thieves knew in advance that the fuel rods represent a health 
hazard. 
  [A. Zolotkov, engineer of the Murmansk Maritime Shipping 
Company radiation safety service, identified by caption] 
Nothing like this has ever happened in Murmansk before. 
However, I am convinced that but for our mismanagement and 
negligence this theft would not have taken place. All it needs 
is to commission the branch railroad built long ago for the 
Northern Fleet military base in Zapadnaya Litsa and the 
equivalent civilian nuclear fleet enterprise for this fuel 
transit center to be dispensed with. [video shows numerous views 
of docks, warships, submarines, merchant ships, interview] 
[151034] 

</TEXT>

