<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> TAJIKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Uranium Plant Changes to Gold Refining Production </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0912182393 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1500 GMT 9 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD0912182393 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Unidentified correspondent] For the first time an 
Ostankino camera crew has visited the most secret facility where 
the explosive filling for the first Soviet atomic bombs was 
made. The Vostokredmet industrial association, which until 
recently mined and refined uranium, is situated in a suburb of 
Khudzhand, an oblast center of Tajikistan. Thirty-five thousand 
people, mostly Russians, who live and work at and around the 
site have suddenly become unwanted by anyone, including Russia, 
in a republic in the grip of a military confrontation. But the 
golden minds and hands of these people have done everything to 
save the enterprise. The construction of a gold refining 
production line is now almost complete at the combine, which 
will allow independent Tajikistan to have its gold in ingots by 
the New Year holiday. Specialists at the combine designed and 
built all the refining equipment themselves. [passage omitted] 
[Video shows fields, machinery, lathes, panel marked "F-16 
Electronic Casting Machine"] 

</TEXT>

