<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk To Submit START I Treaty to Parliament Again </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3011174393 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1606 GMT 30 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3011174393 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] During a telephone conversation with U.S. President 
Bill Clinton, Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk stated that he 
would submit the START-I Treaty to the parliament to be elected 
on March 27, the White House' spokesperson Dee Dee Meyers 
announced in Washington. 
  As we reported earlier, on November 19, the Ukrainian 
parliament ratified the START-I Treaty and the Lisbon Protocol 
with numerous reservations which, in Moscow's opinion, 
undermines the regime of nonproliferation of nuclear weapons. To 
quote Meyers, these reservations disappointed President Clinton. 
  The Ukrainian president's Staff informed Interfax that the 
telephone talks between Clinton and Kravchuk had lasted for 30 
minutes and that no one had been informed of the details. 
  Besides the ratification of the START-I Treaty, the two 
leaders discussed "the economic situation in Ukraine," said a 
representative of the president's Staff. 
  He also said that Clinton had proposed searching for ways of 
implementing the START-I Treaty and expressed readiness to help 
Ukraine solve its economic problems. 
  The Ukrainian and U.S. presidents discussed ways of 
attaining 
agreements on U.S. financial and economic assistance in 
Ukraine's nuclear disarmament, on compensation for the nuclear 
materials and on guarantees of Ukrainian security," he told 
Interfax. 
  He also said that the two leaders had discussed details of 
Kravchuk's forthcoming visit to the U.S. during which 
Ukrainian-U.S. economic cooperation will be discussed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

