<H3> <TI>   Uranium-Smuggling Incidents Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further Report on Missing Uranium </H4>
<F P=102> NC2911150493 Paris AFP in English 1425 GMT 29 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> NC2911150493 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Nov 29 (AFP) -- Turkish police are hunting 
5.5 kilograms (12 pounds) of missing uranium, which may have 
been stolen from Chernobyl nuclear power station, police said 
Monday. 
  It is part of a 10 kilogram batch of the radioactive 
material, the remainder of which was recovered Thursday in 
Bursa, western Turkey, in an undercover operation. 
  Three Georgians were slightly wounded when they were 
arrested 
after trying to sell the uranium to disguised police officers. 
Their identities were still not revealed Monday by police. 
  The seized material has been sent to a nuclear research 
centre in Istanbul for tests, as police look for links with a 
smaller haul of uranium in October in Istanbul. 
  In the earlier incident police arrested five Turks and three 
Iranians allegedly attempting to sell 2.5 kilos of uranium, 
which the Istanbul research centre said was of insufficient 
quality for the manufacture of a nuclear bomb. 
  Five of the group, including one Iranian, were jailed for 
the 
"illegal trafficking of nuclear material" by a court in Istanbul. 
  Parts of the Chernobyl nuclear power station in Ukraine are 
still in operation despite a massive explosion in one of its 
reactors in April 1986 which caused the world's worst peace-time 
nuclear disaster, releasing a cloud of radioactive dust across 
Europe. 

</TEXT>

