<H3> <TI>   Reports on Iranian-DPRK Missile Test Agreement Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0212161293 Tehran IRNA in English 1543 GMT 2 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD0212161293 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran Dec. 2, IRNA -- An informed political source 
here Thursday categorically denied Western circles claim on 
conclusion of a long-range missile test treaty between the 
Islamic Republic of Iran and the Democratic Peoples Republic of 
Korea (DPRK). 
  Recently some American and European media carried reports on 
the likelihood of Pyongyang's selling long-range Scud missiles 
to Tehran as well as testing of the Nodong-1 missiles in Iran. 
  The Iranian source reiterated that Tehran and Pyongyang have 
signed no contract either on testing or purchase of long-range 
missiles. 
  Experts believe that bringing up of such issues aims at 
intriguing the regional states, the rich Arab states in 
particular, to purchase more Western arms. He further added 
that launching of the so-called joint maneuvers of the Persian 
gulf littoral states with Western countries are also in this 
direction. 
  He made it clear that manufacture and purchase of 
conventional weapons for defending the territorial integrity of 
the Islamic Republic of Iran is very natural. 
  He said the West by raising such fabricated news aims at 
intriguing an arms race in the region. 
  President 'Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani in his recent 
interview with Egyptian journalist, Hassanain Haykal, said that 
Iran enjoys a powerful missile technology. 

</TEXT>

