<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Says DPRK Inspection Continuity Seriously Jeopardized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0312015893 Seoul YONHAP in English 0144 GMT 3 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> SK0312015893 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, Dec. 3 (YONHAP) -- Hans Blix, 
director-general of the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA), reported a serious deterioration in the continuity of 
North Korea's nuclear safeguards to a meeting of the IAEA Board 
of Governors Friday. 
  Some cameras, which have been monitoring North Korea's 
nuclear facilities and material, are no longer running, he said. 
  It is becoming more difficult for the IAEA to confirm that 
North Korea is not diverting declared material from peaceful 
purposes, Blix told the board. 
  It has become impossible for the IAEA to have meaningful 
assurance that North Korea is using its nuclear material and 
facilities for peaceful purposes, he said. 
  If North Korea does not cooperate with the IAEA, he warned, 
the inspection continuity of the nuclear safeguards might 
deteriorate to a state from where it cannot be restored. 
  The IAEA must visit and inspect nuclear material and 
facilities in North Korea to determine if North Korea has 
diverted declared material from peaceful purposes. 
  North Korea has not allowed the IAEA to do normal inspection 
activities at its nuclear facilities since February and the 
situation is worsening as time goes by, he said. 
  He said that the IAEA is ready for dialogue and consultation 
with Pyongyang and to send an inspection mission anytime North 
Korea is ready to accept it to carry out its work for 
full-fledged implementation of nuclear safeguards, including 
access to additional information and visits to additional places. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

