<H3> <TI>   First Consignment of Iraqi Irradiated Fuel Flown to Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0612125193 Paris AFP in English 1205 GMT 6 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> NC0612125193 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, Dec 6 (AFP)--A first consignment of 
irradiated fuel from Iraq's nuclear programme has been flown to 
Russia for disposal, a U.N. source said Monday [6 December]. 
  Maurizio Zifferero, assistant director general of the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), has said around 35 
kilograms (77 pounds) of irradiated fuel is to be transferred to 
Russia. 
  A first shipment was flown out on board an Antonov-124 
transport plane from al-Habbaniyah airport west of Baghdad on 
Sunday, the U.N. source said without specifying the quantity. 
  "The second and final consignment will be shipped out early 
next year," the source said. 
  Iraq agreed to have its irradiated nuclear fuel removed 
during a visit in April by Zifferero at the head of a team of 
nuclear inspectors. 
  Zifferero has refused to give the precise cost of the multi- 
million-dollar operation, which is to paid for by Iraq. 
  The IAEA dispatched around 12 kilogrammes (26 pounds) of 
enriched uranium to Russia last month. 
  The United Nations ordered the destruction of Iraq's nuclear 
programme under Gulf war ceasefire resolutions eliminating its 
weapons of mass destruction. 

</TEXT>

