<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam, Clinton Give Mixed Response to DPRK Offer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0812012093 Seoul YONHAP in English 0106 GMT 8 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> SK0812012093 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Dec. 8 (YONHAP) -- Presidents Kim Yong-sam 
and Bill Clinton agreed in a telephone conversation Tuesday that 
North Korea's nuclear inspection offer contains some elements 
that deserve a positive reaction from South Korea and the United 
States, but that it is insufficient and unsatisfactory as a 
whole. 
  The two presidents felt that the offer made by North Korea 
on 
Friday requires basic consideration regarding the future of the 
Korean peninsula, and agreed to take advantage of the 
opportunity within reason, Presidential Spokesman Yi Kyong-chae 
said Wednesday. 
  Yi said that making use of the opportunity within reason 
meant that the presidents had agreed to consider elements of the 
offer and not reject it entirely. 
  In their 30-minute conversation, Clinton conveyed the firm 
and resolute U.S. stance on the North Korean nuclear issue and 
Kim stressed the need for close cooperation between their 
countries in dealing with the issue, Yi said. 
  They agreed to continue discussing details of a joint South 
Korea-U.S. approach to the North Korean nuclear issue at a 
working level. 
  Chong Chong-uk, senior presidential secretary for foreign 
affairs and national security, will fly to Washington to meet 
with National Security Adviser Anthony Lake for talks on the 
approach. 
  Yi said the presidents discussed tariffication of rice and 
rice market opening, but he refused to reveal the content of 
their discussion because negotiations between the two 
governments are under way in Geneva. 
  The negotiations are expected to make progress on the basis 
of the presidential conversation, officials said. 
  On Dec. 3, Kim reportedly met a high-ranking U.S. Government 
official at his office to ask for U.S. understanding of Korea's 
unique situation in Uruguay Round negotiations on rice market 
opening. 
  The telephone conversation was the first between the two 
presidents using a hot line that was opened in July. 

</TEXT>

