<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Says DPRK Offer on Nuclear Issue `Not Sufficient' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0812012993 Seoul YONHAP in English 0120 GMT 8 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> SK0812012993 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Dec. 8 (YONHAP) -- The Russian Government 
said Tuesday that North Korea's acceptance of partial nuclear 
inspection represents a step forward, but not sufficient enough 
to lead to a fundamental solution of the problem. 
  North Korea's expression of its willingness to accept 
international inspection on some nuclear facilities showed it 
was turning to a positive position in light of the opinion of 
the international community, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Gregory 
Karasin told reporters. 
  The proposal does not, however, lead to a fundamental 
solution of the problem, which calls for full implementation of 
its obligations under the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty and a 
guarantee of uninterrupted nuclear inspection, Karasin said. 
  The Russian Government hopes the problem of banning nuclear 
proliferation on the Korean peninsula will be resolved through 
constructive dialogue and mutual cooperation between North Korea 
and the International Atomic Energy Agency at an early date, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

