<H3> <TI>   ROK's Han Says Measures `Inevitable' if DPRK Refuses 
Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0812034993 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0315 GMT 8 
Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> SK0812034993 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Advisory Council on Democratic and Peaceful 
Unification Policy held a joint meeting of its Management and 
Standing Committees on 8 December. At the meeting, government 
offices concerned delivered reports on the current status 
regarding the North Korean nuclear issue and South-North 
relations. The Advisory Council adopted a four-point resolution 
including a point urging an early solution of the North Korean 
nuclear problem. 
  In the resolution, the Advisory Council on Democratic and 
Peaceful Unification Policy urged North Korea to accept 
transparent nuclear inspections and to resume the South-North 
dialogue. It also urged the Governments of South and North 
Korea to take active and immediate measures for meetings and 
reunion of separated family members, which all the countrymen 
desire. 
  In his report, Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu said: The ROK 
and the United States made it clear that it would be difficult 
to continue U.S.-North Korean contacts and international 
measures [kukchejok chawonesoui taecho] will be inevitable 
unless North Korea accepts inspections by the International 
Atomic Energy Agency and accedes to the South-North envoy 
exchange for discussions on the nuclear issue. 

</TEXT>

