<F P=101> JAPAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   White Paper Calls Plutonium Safety Standards `Strict' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3011031293 Tokyo KYODO in English 0245 GMT 30 Nov 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW3011031293 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Nov. 30 KYODO -- Japan's plutonium safety 
standards are so strict that even an unforeseen major accident 
at the nation's fast-breeder reactor Monju would not endanger 
nearby residents, the 1993 White Paper on nuclear safety said 
Tuesday [30 November]. 
  The Director General of the Science and Technology Agency, 
Satsuki Eda, presented the paper to the cabinet Tuesday morning. 
  The paper includes a special section on plutonium use in 
advance of Monju's scheduled April 1994 criticality, the moment 
when the reactor's fuel achieves a chain reaction. 
  The reactor, at Tsuruga in Fukui Prefecture, uses plutonium, 
which is 260,000 times more radioactive than uranium. 
  The paper states that since plutonium is a byproduct of the 
burning of uranium, there is no intrinsic difference between the 
two substances. 
  But the paper notes that the nation's standards for 
acceptable irradiation levels also pertain to bone and lungs, 
which absorb plutonium easily. 
  At Monju, for example, the paper said that even if a major 
accident occurs -- an event it said is technically impossible -- 
safety measures are so tight that nearby residents would receive 
less than the allowable levels of radiation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

