<H3> <TI>   Message to IAEA Refusing To Accept Inspection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0112231593 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2210 GMT 1 
Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> SK0112231593 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Cha Man-sun from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] It has been learned that there has been no change at 
all in the position of North Korea, which has refused the 
overall inspection [chonmyon sachal] by the International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA], even after the ROK and U.S. leaders 
announced a principle of settling the North Korean nuclear issue. 
  North Korea sent a message to Hans Blix, director general of 
the IAEA, yesterday [1 December], a day before the meeting of 
governors of the IAEA is held, and showed a negative response by 
saying that it cannot accept the overall inspection at present. 
  The IAEA said that it had received a reply message from 
North 
Korea in connection with its 24 November message urging the 
North Korean side to accept the overall inspection, but the 
contents of the message shows that there is no change at all in 
its previous position that it would only allow the change of 
monitoring equipment. 
  Also, IAEA authorities say that the IAEA may declare North 
Korea as a country that has not fulfilled the Nuclear Safeguard 
Accords unless it allows access to experts of the suspected 
nuclear facilities. 
  An IAEA official said the IAEA has no other choice than to 
refer the North Korean issue for the second time to the UN 
Security Council around the end of this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

