<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BRAZIL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreement for Inspection of Nuclear Installations Signed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0912001593 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 8 
Dec 93 p 18 </F>

<F P=103> PY0912001593 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Tania Malheiros in Rio de Janeiro] </F>
  [Text] On 7 December, Senator Dirceu Carneiro (PSDB-SC 
[Brazilian Social Democracy Party-Santa Catarina State]) told O 
ESTADO DE SAO PAULO that he has received a note from Foreign 
Relations Minister Celso Amorim informing him that the 
quadripartite agreement that the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) negotiated in Vienna, Austria, will open Brazilian 
nuclear installations to international inspection for the first 
time. Carneiro explained that the agreement "is a landmark in 
the history of international nuclear safeguards." 
  He said that the agreement explains how the IAEA will 
inspect 
nuclear installations in Brazil. Carneiro is the speaker for 
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and was in charge of the 
negotiations between the Senate and the Brazilian administration. 
  The timing of the visits was the most controversial aspect 
of 
the issue. Carneiro said the IAEA agreed to notify in advance 
its intention to inspect Brazilian nuclear installations and to 
make the inspection only after their construction is finished. 
"The IAEA wanted to inspect installations while construction 
was under way, but Brazil did not agree," Carneiro said. 
  He also reported that from the diplomatic viewpoint the 
Brazilian negotiators gained status in the eyes of the 
international community. "Brazil tied its ratification of the 
accord to the fulfillment of certain conditions, unlike many 
other countries that did not follow suit," Carneiro stated. 
  According to the senator, the IAEA was pressuring to gain 
control over nuclear energy in Brazil. The agency wanted, among 
other things, to visit Brazilian installations whenever it 
received a report that Brazil was using nuclear energy for 
nonpeaceful objectives. "Brazil did not accept this and 
demanded that unscheduled inspections comply with auxiliary 
regulations that clearly establish how this should be done, and 
the IAEA agreed," the senator explained. "This was the aspect 
that countries fear most, which is why Brazil has never signed 
the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT), which will be 
reviewed in 1995." 
  The senator also reported that the Brazilian-Argentine 
Agency 
for Accounting and Control of Nuclear Material (ABACC), not the 
IAEA, will control nuclear material in Brazil. "This will be 
done to make sure that the uranium enriched in Brazil using 
Brazilian technology will not be diverted to manufacturing arms 
in Brazil or abroad," Carneiro said. The Brazilian Senate will 
have to ratify the agreement signed with the IAEA early in 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-60654 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptnd001___94023" </HT>


