<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> CHILE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Congress Ratifies Tlatelolco Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0312144093 Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 26 Nov 93 p C2 </F>
<F P=103> PY0312144093 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago EL MERCURIO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Valparaiso -- The draft agreement on the approval of 
several amendments to the Tlatelolco Treaty is ready for 
publication in the official gazette following registration at 
the Controller's Office. 
  This draft agreement modifies the Treaty for the 
Proscription 
of Nuclear Weapons in Latin America and the Caribbean, which was 
formulated in April 1969 and was ratified by Chile in October 
1974. 
  This international treaty, signed in the Mexican town of 
Tlatelolco, seeks to establish zones and environments free of 
nuclear weapons. It is the first of its type encompassing an 
extensive and heavily populated zone like Latin America and the 
Caribbean. 
  The changes seek to include countries which obtained their 
independence since the implementation of said treaty (Belize and 
Guyana), to change in the treaty's name, and to include the 
Caribbean nations. 
  Finally, by suggestion of Chile, Argentina, and Brazil, 
essential amendments are being made to make the treaty's control 
system more operational without affecting its essential 
political principles and objectives. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-60655 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptnd001___94024" </HT>


<HEADER>
