<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> CUBA </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Hears Demand on Change in Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0412125393 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 4 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> FL0412125393 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, at the International Atomic Energy Agency 
headquartered in Vienna, Austria, Cuba demanded the elimination 
of the two-category state system mentioned in the 
nonproliferation of nuclear weapons treaty: those which do not 
possess these weapons, and the known nuclear powers. Andres 
Garcia de la Cruz, executive secretary of the Atomic Energy 
Commission of Cuba, said that the agency should demand that the 
known nuclear powers honor their commitment to end the nuclear 
arms race and to disarm, a commitment set 25 years ago. Garcia 
de la Cruz made these comments during a meeting of the agency's 
Board of Governors, and he insisted on the adoption of a new 
policy to strengthen the efficiency of the safeguard 
[salvaguardia] system. 
  Garcia de la Cruz also pointed out that, before proceeding 
with the implementation of these programs, it is necessary to 
establish an adequate legal framework and to proceed with the 
programs without waiting for the results of the technical and 
economic evaluation to determine their implications from the 
legal standpoint. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

