<F P=101> PAKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on Pressler's Visit, Foreign Assistance Act </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0112162993 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in English 
1600 GMT 1 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> BK0112162993 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pakistan has expressed the hope that a rewrite of 
the American Foreign Assistance Act to be undertaken by Congress 
will further the objectives of nuclear nonproliferation jointly 
shared by the United States and Pakistan. A Foreign Office 
spokesman said in Islamabad today that Pakistan views the 
Pressler Amendment as a discriminatory law. He said Senator 
Pressler is likely to visit Pakistan by the middle of this 
month, and Pakistan will try to put across its point of view on 
the discriminatory nature of this law. 
  Replying to a question, the spokesman said Pakistan is 
continuously negotiating with different governments on different 
means to achieve the objectives of nonproliferation in South 
Asia,. He, however, said Pakistan has not received any specific 
proposal from the United States recently. 

</TEXT>

