<H3> <TI>   Bhutto Clarifies Nuclear Position, Views U.S. Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0712144293 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 7 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> BK0712144293 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister Ms. Benazir Bhutto has said 
there will be no roll back of our peaceful nuclear program. 
Talking informally to journalists in Islamabad today, she 
answered a number of questions, including those on the nuclear 
issue and the Pakistan- American relations. 
  [Begin Bhutto recording] With the United States, we have 
also started a two-way dialogue to see how the two countries can 
overcome the problem that has arisen in their relationship. We 
cannot roll back [the nuclear program] and this is the position 
we have tried to explain to the United States that we cannot 
roll back. At the same time, we have explained to the United 
States that we support nonproliferation and we seek to have a 
peaceful nuclear program and so long as there is no threat to 
our security, our program will continue to be peaceful. 
  We feel that the Pressler Amendment is unjustified because 
it 
is not only discriminatory, but it does not serve the purpose of 
regional nonproliferation. In fact, it is a veto in Indian 
hands. 
  So, we are trying to pull Pakistan out of international 
isolation. We are trying to put Kashmir in its proper 
perspective and we are trying to put the Pressler Amendment in 
its proper perspective. Obviously, this is not liked by the 
opposition because our achievements only highlight their 
failure, and, so, they are kicking up a big dust about a 
non-issue. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

