<F P=101> NORTH KOREA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nodong-1 Can Be Fired From Mobile Launcher </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2412020193 Seoul YONHAP in English 0137 GMT 24 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> SK2412020193 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Dec. 24 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has developed 
mobile launchers for its Nodong-1 missiles, making it extremely 
difficult to intercept the missiles or to locate launch 
facilities and knock them out of commission, the YOMIURI SHIMBUN 
newspaper reported Friday. 
  ``North Korea will put the Nodong-1 missile into operational 
deployment next year,'' the YOMIURI quoted international 
military sources as saying. 
  ``When North Korea succeeded in test firing the Nodong-1 in 
late March, it was launched from a fixed platform, so we thought 
that changing the location was very difficult,'' a Japanese 
Defense Agency spokesman was quoted as saying. ``But later the 
United States and Japan learned that a mobile launch was 
possible by analyzing intelligence.'' 
  ``The Nodong-1 is so large that launching it from a ship 
proved impossible, however,'' the senior official reportedly 
said. 
  ``Since it does not use a fixed launch platform, it is hard 
to discover the launch location. Moreover North Korea has 
transferred most of its military facilities underground, so an 
attack by U.S. forces on the missile facilities is difficult.'' 
  The Nodong-1, a modified Scud-C ballistic missile having a 
1,000-kilometer range, is capable of reaching most areas of 
Japan except parts of Hokkaido. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

