<H3> <TI>   Further on DPRK Comments on 20 December Contact With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2212142293 Beijing XINHUA in English 1354 GMT 22 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW2212142293 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, Dec. 22 (XINHUA) -- A Foreign Ministry 
spokesman of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) 
said today that he is expecting a response from the United 
States to DPRK's new proposal over the disputed nuclear issue. 
  He told reporters that the two countries were in contact on 
Monday [20 December] in New York and the DPRK had put forward a 
new plan in view of the U.S. suggestion proposed on 10 December. 
  The spokesman, releasing no details of DPRK's proposal, said 
nevertheless that it was ``reasonable'' and would 
``satisfactorily help solve the nuclear problems on the Korean 
peninsula.'' 
  The DPRK and the U.S. have failed to reach any agreement 
during their regular ``contacts'' throughout December. 
  Meanwhile, the United Nations Secretary-General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali is reportedly traveling to the DPRK on Friday 
following his visit to the Republic of Korea. 
  He is the first UN chief to visit DPRK in the past ten years 
and is expected to hold talks with DPRK leaders on the 
deadlocked nuclear issue. 

</TEXT>

