</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-60693 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptnd002___94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TND-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:PROLIFERATION ISSUES 

<DATE1>  18 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Egyptian Editorial Urges Israel To Heed UN Resolution on 
Nuclear Ban </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1912090693 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0600 GMT 19 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> NC1912090693 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 19 Dec (MENA)--The newspaper AL-AHRAM 
comments in an editorial today on the UN General Assembly's 
recent resolution urging all Middle Eastern countries to join 
the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty and stop developing or 
producing nuclear bombs. 
  The paper notes that Egypt was among the first countries to 
join the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty in the 1960's, while 
Israel refused and continues to refuse to sign the treaty or 
commit itself to the nonpossession of nuclear arms. 
  Referring to the UN inspection committees that have 
monitored 
Iraq's airspace and territory since it invaded Kuwait to ensure 
that it does not possess the capability to manufacture weapons 
of mass destruction, AL-AHRAM says a similar measure has not 
been applied to Israel even though it does not allow its nuclear 
installations to be inspected. 
  The paper urges Israel to comply with the UN General 
Assembly 
resolution, as the other countries in the region have, in line 
with the current effort toward establishing peace and 
good-neighborliness among them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

